data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider's sync-over-async bridge was **opt-in** (via `CosmosOptionsExtension` / `EnableSyncOverAsync`). In .NET 11 that bridge is **removed entirely**. Every synchronous LINQ operator (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`) and `SaveChanges()` on the Cosmos provider will throw an **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime — there is no opt-in anymore.

### The fix: convert to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
1. Return `Task<T>` (or `Task`) instead of `T`/`void`.
2. Replace `ToList` → `ToListAsync`, `First` → `FirstAsync`, `Count` → `CountAsync`, `SaveChanges` → `SaveChangesAsync`.
3. `await` each call; mark methods `async`.
4. Rename methods with `Async` suffix (convention, not required).
5. Remove the `EnableSyncOverAsync` configuration — it no longer compiles.

This will propagate `async` up the call chain to your controllers/services, so plan for that ripple effect.
